[{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"# Attributes that influence the look in CSS\n\nWith CSS you can style the looks of an element. In this Stylebook you will learn some of the most useful attributes to change the look of an element. For the examples we will style a `h1`-element and we will use an _element selector_."},{"kind":2,"language":"html","value":"<h1>Hello CSS!</h1>"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"## Border\n\nLet's first check out the different properties the border of an element can have.\n\n### `border-style`\n\nWith the `border-style` property you can set the style of a border. For example, you can use `solid`, `dashed` or `dotted` as value to change the style of the border."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  border-style: solid;\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"### `border-width`\n\nWith the `border-width` property you can set the width of a border. You can use any unit, for example `px` or `em`. The default value is `medium`. If you want, you can assign a different width for every side of the border. You can find more infos about it in the reference [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/border-width)."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  border-width: 0.5em;\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"### `border-color`\n\nWith the `border-color` property you can set the color of a border. As with the `border-width`, you can set each side individually. Possible values for colors are hex-codes, starting with the _hashtag_ `#`, defining the RGB values with the `rgb` or the `rgba` function, or using a keyword like `blue` or `transparent`. If you want to find out more about how to define a color, you can find the reference [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/color_value)."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  border-color: #ffaa00;\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"### `border`\n\nThere is also a shorthand syntax that let you define everything in one line. If you use the `border` attribute, you first set the _style_, next the _width_, and last the _color_."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  border: dashed 4px #000000;\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"To continue with the examples, we set the `border-style` to `hidden`, so it doesn't interfere with the rest."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  border-style: hidden;\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"## Background\n\nYou can set different attributes of the background of an element.\n\n### `background-color`\n\nThe first thing we want to try is to set the `background-color` of our element. Please refer to the `border-color` attribute for possible color values."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  background-color: rgb(128, 0, 128);\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"### `background-image`\n\nNext we want to set the `background-image` attribute of our element. We use the `url()` function to load an image. Inside the brackets we enter the path to the image. We can enter an absolute url, starting with _https_ or a relative path.\n\nYou can find out more about the various other attributes you can set to control the `background-image` [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/background-image)."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  background-image: url(https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528460033278-a6ba57020470);\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"You can also use it to fill the background with a _gradient_. If you wanna find out more about it, you can check out [this article](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Images/Using_CSS_gradients).\n\n### `background`\n\nAs with most CSS attributes, you can use the `background` attribute as a shorthand syntax to define attributes at once. You can look at the [reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/background) to get a better idea how to use it."},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"h1 {\n  background: linear-gradient(red, yellow);\n}"}]